\begin_layout Subsection
LADSPA Plugins
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One great feature of the program is that you can apply LADSPA plugins to
 the music.
 You can use the equalizer of your choice instead of a built-in one, along
 with other plugins.
 You can process your sound with Aqualung in ways that the author of this
 program never thought of.
 A recommended set is TAP-plugins, downloadable from 
\family typewriter
http://tap-plugins.sf.net
\family default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Of course, faithful reproduction of music does not require or permit pervasive
 signal processing, since that is not the purpose of such activity.
 However, the technology is at your disposal and it's up to you to use or
 misuse it.
 It may be necessary to adapt your listening gear to the acoustic environment,
 using small amounts of equalization preferably in a subtractive manner.
 In addition to this, I also like to spice my tracks with a small amount
 of tubewarmth to feel that warm tube sound even with my transistor amplifiers,
 and to bring out even the finest details of the music.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The plugin chain you build is automatically saved and restored, so once
 you get it right for your listening environment, you should rarely need
 to touch it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some tricks concerning the LADSPA patch builder:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Multiple plugins can be selected from the available plugins list and added
 at once by clicking on the `Add button' or pressing `a' or `A'.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A single plugin can be added immediately by double-clicking it in the available
 plugins list.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Plugins in the running list can be (un)bypassed with the middle mouse button.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Running plugins' configuration window can be brought up by double-clicking
 on them (same as clicking on the `Configure' button).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If a plugin is selected in the running plugins list, pressing delete will
 remove it (same as pressing the `Remove' button).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Running plugins can be rearranged at any time (changing the order in which
 they are processed) via dragging them with the mouse.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In the configuration windows of plugins, setting input controls back to
 their default value is possible by shift-clicking on the slider.
 This does not work for toggled or integer inputs (those that don't have
 a slider displayed for them).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
JACK Port Setup
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If you use JACK output, you need this dialog to route the outputs of the
 program somewhere (most likely to the playback ports representing the soundcard
 driver).
 If you want the outputs to be connected automatically to the first two
 hardware playback devices, use the -a (or 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard

{-}{-}
\end_layout

\end_inset

auto) command line option.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the left, each output port has a list of its current connections.
 By clicking on any list item, that connection will be removed.
 The `Clear connections' button removes all connections from the output
 ports.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The notebook on the right has a page for all client programs and hardware
 devices available to the JACK server.
 Naturally only those are shown which are data sinks (hardware playback
 devices or inputs of JACK clients), thus connectable to outputs which are
 data sources.
 By selecting a notebook page, you will see a list of that client's input
 ports.
 Clicking on a list item connects the port to the currently selected Aqualung
 output port (which has a blue header).
 You can change the selected output port by clicking on the unselected (grey)
 list header.
 When you add connections to the output ports, the selection alters between
 the two outputs so connecting both outputs is very fast and easy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If you start up another JACK client while the dialog is open, you may press
 the `Rescan' button to make it appear in the notebook.
 Closing and re-opening the dialog has the same effect, since JACK ports
 are re-read and a new dialog instance is built every time.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Skin Chooser
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This dialog lets you choose from the available skins at any time.
 All officially supported skins are shipped with Aqualung, and installed
 in the system-wide skin directory during `make install'.
 Skins placed in the local skin directory will only be locally available,
 which is useful for developing new skins or experimenting with the existing
 ones.
 If there are skins in the system-wide directory and the local directory
 having the same name, the local one takes precedence.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
System Tray Support
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When compiled with Systray support, Aqualung will place its icon in the
 system tray (notification area), and lets all of its windows to be closed
 while still playing music.
 In this mode pressing the upper right X on the main window will not exit
 the program, only hide its windows.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Clicking on the systray icon with the left mouse button will toggle visibility
 of the program's windows.
 Clicking with the right button will bring up a popup menu allowing showing/hidi
ng the windows, basic cueing, and quitting Aqualung.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The systray icon has a tooltip displaying the same text as the main window's
 title.
 So it's easy to see what track is currently playing, and also the Aqualung
 instance ID (in case of more instances).
 
\end_layout

